<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-273-522  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 273 522.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 15 1989 v23 n20 p52(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Selling, or selling out. (selling internally-developed informationsystems technology) (Taking Charge) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ryan, Alan J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The selling of internally-developed information systems technologyis the subject of much debate, especially when the technology issold to direct competitors.andP;  Selling internally-developedinformation technology to a non-competitor is a lucrative andusually safe practice.andP;  Selling to the competition, however, is adangerous practice and potentially very damaging.andP;  A studyconducted by Big Eight accounting firm Arthur Young and MITpredicts that the selling of information systems technology willbecome common in the 1990s.andP;  The appeal of sellinginternally-developed technology is that information systemsdepartments could become self sufficient.andP;  Companies should notsell to competitors, however, as the short-term gains will mostlikely be wiped out in the long run.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information SystemsMarketingCompanies.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>